WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6.0 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:12.000
Hello, this is 6.0 English from BBCLearningEnglish. I'm Phil.

4
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:15.000
And I'm Beth. Are you a big reader Phil?

5
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Sure, I enjoy reading and it's also a great way to pass the time on my daily commute to work.

6
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:24.000
But reading isn't just a nice thing to do.

7
00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:29.000
It's an essential skill, something you need for everyday activities,

8
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:35.000
whether that's finding out the news by reading a newspaper, or buying groceries by reading the labels.

9
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:45.000
And that's why I was shocked by a recent UN report estimating that around the world over 700 million adults are illiterate,

10
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:48.000
which means they can't read or write.

11
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
Wow, that's a huge number of people excluded from doing basic day-to-day things.

12
00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:58.000
So what can we do to get more adults reading and writing?

13
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:04.000
This program will be hearing about projects into very different countries trying to do just that.

14
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:08.000
That is usual, we'll be learning some useful new vocabulary as well.

15
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
But first, I have a question for you, Phil.

16
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
I mentioned a recent UN report on the high numbers of people unable to read and write,

17
00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:21.000
but illiteracy is not a new problem.

18
00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:27.000
Since 1967, the UN has been highlighting the importance of literacy,

19
00:01:27.000 --> 00:01:33.000
being able to read and write, with a day-up celebration called International Literacy Day.

20
00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:36.000
But when does it take place?

21
00:01:36.000 --> 00:01:39.000
Is it a, the 8th of March?

22
00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:43.000
B, the 8th of June, or C, the 8th of September?

23
00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
I think international literacy day is on the 8th of September.

24
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:53.000
Okay, Phil, we'll find out if that's correct at the end of the program.

25
00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:58.000
The biggest reason people grow up illiterate is not going to school,

26
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:03.000
and that's especially true for people living in the coastal towns of Bangladesh,

27
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:07.000
because these towns, flood regularly, families are always on the move,

28
00:02:07.000 --> 00:02:10.000
making it hard for children to get an education.

29
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:16.000
The Friendship Project teaches reading and writing to groups of Bangladesh, you women and girls.

30
00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:22.000
They also teach numeracy, which means the ability to do basic maths like counting and adding up.

31
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:30.000
Here, one student, Rashida, explains the impact it's had on her to BBC World Service program, people fixing the world.

32
00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:37.000
My parents never sent me to schools, and I've suffered from not being able to read and write.

33
00:02:37.000 --> 00:02:42.000
My children were embarrassed that I was illiterate. I couldn't even do basic accounting.

34
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
Until now, I've had to use my fingerprint as a signature as I was illiterate.

35
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:54.000
But now I can sign my name because I can read and write the alphabet, and I'll also be able to keep an account of my expenses.

36
00:02:54.000 --> 00:02:57.000
No one can cheat me anymore.

37
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Before the Friendship Project, Rashida couldn't write her signature, her name written in her own handwriting.

38
00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:09.000
Instead, she had to use her fingerprint.

39
00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:20.000
Now, Rashida has learnt the alphabet and also some basic maths, so she knows how much money she spent and how much she has left.

40
00:03:20.000 --> 00:03:26.000
This means no one can cheat her, can trick or swindle her into taking her money.

41
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:36.000
The Friendship Project is free and so far over 11,000 adults have completed it, but it's not just developing countries that struggle with literacy.

42
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:47.000
Our second project takes place much closer to home, the north of England, where charity read easy matches adult learners with trained volunteers for one to one lessons.

43
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:54.000
In the UK, one in six adults struggle with reading and writing, including Peter.

44
00:03:54.000 --> 00:04:01.000
Peter had hearing problems as a child, fell behind at school and never learnt to read.

45
00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:08.000
Here he is, talking with BBC World Service Program, people fixing the world.

46
00:04:08.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Everyone takes for granted that you're to open a letter and you read it.

47
00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
Before I let you write, I used to have to knock a neighbor's dog, could you read this for me?

48
00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.000
Can you imagine the embarrassment?

49
00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:26.000
I've tried college, twice, nothing works, so as far as I'm concerned, I think I'm stupid.

50
00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:32.000
I'm just one of those people, it's never going away from me, and that was my life.

51
00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:36.000
Many of us take it for granted that everyone can read and write.

52
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:42.000
If you take something for granted, you assume it's true without checking.

53
00:04:42.000 --> 00:04:45.000
Peter had to ask his neighbors to read his letters.

54
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:51.000
Something he found very embarrassing, he thought he was thick, stupid and unintelligent.

55
00:04:52.000 --> 00:05:01.000
Now Peter says learning with readies he has changed his life, he's literate, and is reading his way through the Harry Potterworks.

56
00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And he always celebrates International Literacy Day.

57
00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:07.000
Which reminds me of your question, Beth?

58
00:05:07.000 --> 00:05:11.000
When does the UN's International Literacy Day take place?

59
00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
I said it was on the 8th of September.

60
00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:17.000
And that was the correct answer!

61
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned from this program starting with illiterate, meaning unable to read and write.

62
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:30.000
Numeracy is the ability to understand basic maths, count and add up.

63
00:05:30.000 --> 00:05:35.000
Your signature is your name written in your own handwriting style.

64
00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:39.000
It shows that something has been written or agreed by you.

65
00:05:39.000 --> 00:05:45.000
To cheat someone means to trick or deceive them in order to get their money more valuables.

66
00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
If you take something for granted, you assume that it's true without checking up.

67
00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:54.000
And finally the adjective thick is an informal word for stupid.

68
00:05:54.000 --> 00:06:04.000
Once again, our 6 minutes are up, but remember to join us again next time for more trending topics and useful vocabulary here at 6 minute English.

69
00:06:04.000 --> 00:06:05.000
Goodbye for now!

70
00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Bye!
